 the medieval culture of appearances.At the same time, however, institutions such as law courts and the church, alarmed by the power of talk, sought increasingly to regulate it. Christian moral discourse, literary and visual representation, juristic manuals, and court records reflected concern about talk. This book's authors consider how talk was created and entered into memory. They address such topics as fama's relation to secular law and the preoccupations of the church, its impact on women's lives, and its capacity to shape the concept of literary authorship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aLaw, MedievalxSocial aspects. 0aReputation (Law)zEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 4aLegal History & Studies. 4aMedieval & Renaissance Studies. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh1 aAkehurst, F. R. P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBardsley, Sandy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBowman, Jeffrey A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaviness, Madeline H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCraun, Edwin D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFenster, Thelma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFenster, Thelma, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHorvath, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKuehn, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLord Smail, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNelson, Charles G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmail, Daniel Lord, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWalters, Lori J., econtributor.4ctb4h